[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering test styles**\n\nI'm exploring potential styles for testing. I think tests should generally be public at the top level, while nested ones can be package-private. I'm unsure if test methods should be public, but maybe? I’m also considering the use of a @TempDir field and whether it can be static—probably not. \n\nThere are some concerns about visibility with `AutoValue` classes and how Checkstyle might play into things. The dynamic class loading under Native Image is worrying me too, particularly if ToolProvider is null. I should figure out how to handle custom classloaders better.\n\n**Evaluating dynamic loading issues**\n\nI'm considering potential problems with ServiceLoader throwing unsupported exceptions. The idea is to handle dynamic class loading first and catch any errors. If the native environment allows resource loading but no compiler, that could be a failure point. \n\nShould I adapt to an external compiler instead? It seems ToolProvider could return null, leading to confusion. I could try using `com.sun.tools.javac.api.JavacTool.create()` instead of ToolProvider. It might throw an UnsupportedFeatureError during initialization. I’m wondering if I can avoid running a dynamic compiler entirely in the native environment without skipping tests.\n\n**Examining Native Image execution**\n\nI’m pondering whether skipping early returns during Native Image execution is acceptable. The rule suggests we shouldn’t skip, especially if GraalVM's native-image contains the JDK compiler. \n\nActually, maybe the native image runtime from GraalVM's JDK does include `ToolProvider.getSystemJavaCompiler()`. Native images might not have tools.jar, but with JDK9 and beyond, JavaCompiler is part of the jdk.compiler module, which isn't in the Java SE root. If that module is referenced, perhaps the native image can include it and make the provider available.", "th